ely non-literate peoples around the globe. Recording their dreams, stories, and innermost thoughts in a vast database, Kaplan envisioned future researchers accessing the data through the cutting-edge Readex machine. Almost immediately, however, technological developments and the obsolescence of the theoretical framework rendered the project irrelevant, and eventually it was forgotten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Apr 2020) 0aBig dataxHistoryx20th century. 0aBig dataxHistoryy20th century. 0aDreamsxData processingxHistoryx20th century. 0aDreamsxData processingxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychologyxData processingxHistoryx20th century. 0aPsychologyxData processingxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychologyxResearchxHistoryx20th century. 0aPsychologyxResearchxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociologyxData processingxHistoryx20th century. 0aSociologyxData processingxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociologyxResearchxHistoryx20th century. 0aSociologyxResearchxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300216646423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300216646.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO